recognize the

00:14:46.570 --> 00:14:52.130
many contributions and
achievements that
Asian-Pacific Americans have
made to our

00:14:52.130 --> 00:14:58.100
great nation. Throughout the
history of the
United States the flow of
immigrants into the

00:14:58.100 --> 00:15:05.030
nation has continuously
rejuvenated the
country both economically and
socially.

00:15:05.030 --> 00:15:11.430
Thanks to our history books we
are all aware
of the great influx of
immigrants from Europe

00:15:11.430 --> 00:15:20.700
in the early 1900's, undoubtedly
a crucial piece
of the nation's rich history and
a driver of the

00:15:20.700 --> 00:15:26.070
industrial revolution. We also
learn of the great
influx of African-Americans
during one of the

00:15:26.070 --> 00:15:33.530
most shameful periods of our
nation's history;
however, today the contributions
of the

00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:39.530
African-American culture and
people are
rightfully abundant, well
respected, and highly

00:15:39.530 --> 00:15:46.900
recognized. When it comes to
Asian-Pacific
American contributions, probably
our society

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:52.470
doesn't know as much as they
could or
should. If you were to ask your
average

00:15:52.470 --> 00:15:58.900
citizen walking down the street
to name some
contributions to American
society from

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:04.930
Asian-Pacific Americans, I'm
willing to bet that
the most common answer would be
the

00:16:04.930 --> 00:16:12.600
construction of the railroads in
the 1800's. A
great contribution indeed, but
we have done so

00:16:12.600 --> 00:16:18.000
much more. And it is one of my
goals as the
member of Congress from American
Samoa

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:25.170
to ensure that those many
contributions are
neither forgotten more
dismissed. The term

00:16:25.170 --> 00:16:31.130
Asian-Pacific American
encompasses a
multitude of different cultures,
values, and

00:16:31.130 --> 00:16:41.530
traditions. And while on the
outside that may
seem to pose an obstacle to real
unification,

00:16:41.530 --> 00:16:48.670
it's actually a very powerful
tool that has the
ability to reach much further
and have more

00:16:48.670 --> 00:16:57.830
influence than if we were to all
try to achieve
our separate goals together.
Together we are

00:16:57.830 --> 00:17:06.070
19.4 million strong, and we're
going to keep
growing. Now this year's theme,
"Walk

00:17:06.070 --> 00:17:12.270
Together, Embrace Differences,
Build
Legacies," which I believe is
the perfect theme

00:17:12.270 --> 00:17:21.370
to help solidify the message we
bring as
Asian-Pacific Americans. Walk
together, as I

00:17:21.370 --> 00:17:28.370
stated early, our group is a
vast one
comprised of many different
cultures. We

00:17:28.370 --> 00:17:34.930
must put aside any conflicting
interest for the
greater good of all
Asian-Pacific Americans.

00:17:34.930 --> 00:17:44.530
Embrace differences, well,
instead of pointing
out what makes us different and
biased, let us

00:17:44.530 --> 00:17:51.830
instead highlight a positive way
that makes
each of our cultures unique and
recognize

00:17:51.830 --> 00:17:59.330
what that may do for the greater
good. Build
legacies, those who came before
us have

00:17:59.330 --> 00:18:05.070
really done the hardest work.
They were the
ones who had to fight racial
discrimination and

00:18:05.070 --> 00:18:12.070
a real lack of resources and an
opportunity
which, yes, certainly still
exists today, but

00:18:12.070 --> 00:18:18.670
nowhere near the level at which
those who
preceded us had to deal with.
Let us

00:18:18.670 --> 00:18:24.930
continue to build upon what they
started with
their blood, sweat, and tears,
and if we could

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:31.930
all come together as one while
bringing our
own unique and rich cultures to
the table, we

00:18:31.930 --> 00:18:38.930
can reach levels that not even
those who
paved the way could ever have
imagined. You

00:18:38.930 --> 00:18:46.000
know, a few years back I was
asked to
conduct seminars in the Central
Asian country

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:54.300
of Kazakhstan, part of the
former Soviet
Union. Its capital, Almaty, is
almost as far

00:18:54.300 --> 00:19:02.370
from Moscow as Pago Pago is from
Washington. And so while I was
there many of

00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:10.800
the Kazakh leaders would ask me
what my
nationality was, and I would
always reply, "I'm

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:18.200
an American Samoan," which would
always in
turn elicit the follow-up
question of, "How can

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:26.370
that be? How can you be so far
away from the
United States and yet feel so
American?" I

00:19:26.370 --> 00:19:35.470
said, "Well, it's something we
understand
intuitively, but it's difficult
to put into words for

00:19:35.470 --> 00:19:43.930
other people." How can I be a
Pacific Islander
and a loyal American? Well,
this comfortable

00:19:43.930 --> 00:19:54.000
duality exist side-by-side
within us. And you
know President Ronald Reagan
once said,

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:59.000
"You cannot move to France and
become
French. You cannot move to
Germany and

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:04.830
become German. But you can move
to the
United States and become
American." And

00:20:04.830 --> 00:20:13.430
that is what makes our country
so different
and so remarkable. Beyond the
many private

00:20:13.430 --> 00:20:20.630
and cultural contributions we've
made, Asian-
Americans, Asian-Pacific
Americans also lead

00:20:20.630 --> 00:20:27.630
the way in public service. One
thing I make
sure to remind my colleagues in
Congress

00:20:27.630 --> 00:20:34.830
about whenever the opportunity
presents itself
is the rate of enlistment into
our nation's

00:20:34.830 --> 00:20:43.100
armed forces by Americans who
reside in the
Pacific Region. American
Samoans this

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:51.770
happens to be higher than any
other geographical region in the
country. So for the

00:20:51.770 --> 00:21:01.370
military people who are here
today thank you so much for your
service to our nation. Our

00:21:01.370 --> 00:21:08.700
young men and women put their
lives on the line every day at a
rate 10 times those of here

00:21:08.700 --> 00:21:15.500
in the states. The dedication
to this great nation from our
many cultures cannot be

00:21:15.500 --> 00:21:22.000
underestimated. And I'm proud
to come from a family with a
strong military tradition and a

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:28.230
long line of service men and
service women who sacrificed
much in the name of our

00:21:28.230 --> 00:21:35.770
country. At a time when the
threat of terrorism is so
constant, those of us who live
in small,

00:21:35.770 --> 00:21:42.070
remote Pacific Islands can thank
God for guiding us to a place
that is peaceful and gives

00:21:42.070 --> 00:21:53.200
us a great sense of security.
And I thank God that he made me
a member of a wonderful

00:21:53.200 --> 00:22:00.830
race of people who would leave
that peace and tranquility and
go forth into the world to

00:22:00.830 --> 00:22:08.230
protect their fellow man so that
we can all enjoy our freedom and
way of life. So I want to

00:22:08.230 --> 00:22:14.030
encourage all of you here today
to go out, spread the word on
the contributions to the

00:22:14.030 --> 00:22:22.800
United States that our people
have made. Do not do so
boastfully but rather humbly and

00:22:22.800 --> 00:22:31.100
informatively as is our nature.
It's not our way to thump our
chests like Tarzan or shout from

00:22:31.100 --> 00:22:37.670
the rooftops. We simply put our
noses to the grindstone and work
harder than the guy next

00:22:37.670 --> 00:22:46.400
to us. That is how we will
continue to build upon the
legacy we have begun. I want to

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:52.200
thank the Library of Congress
for allowing me to be here today
to speak to all of you. And

00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:58.300
please know that my office is
open to each and every one of
you should you ever need

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:07.030
assistance or simply want to
come by and say talofa or hello.
God bless the Pacific. God

00:23:07.030 --> 00:23:10.270
bless the United States of
America. Thank you.


