wrote down our entire

00:26:29.270 --> 00:26:33.770
family heritage and sent it to
me. So if you would like to see
that, that is yours for the

00:26:33.770 --> 00:26:41.600
viewing. I guess without further
adieu I will formally begin my
presentation. So David

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:46.370
Mao, Congresswoman, thank you
for joining us today, honored
guests, community

00:26:46.370 --> 00:26:53.870
members, and family as well.
Today is a very important day
for me to be able to speak about

00:26:53.870 --> 00:27:02.230
the journey that I got to just
go through while here at the
Library. The Library is
actually the

00:27:02.230 --> 00:27:07.570
nation's first cultural
institution, if you were not
aware, so I could not think of a
more

00:27:07.570 --> 00:27:15.600
appropriate place to hold an
event such like this. Fa'asamoa,
the Samoan way are words

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:20.300
that I didn't quite understand
when I arrived. They are words
that as a child were

00:27:20.300 --> 00:27:28.370
impressed on my heart.
Fa'asamoa are the words also
imprinted on the sacred tattoos
of

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:37.270
my family members, on the arm of
my father, the iconic art
representations found on the

00:27:37.270 --> 00:27:44.370
skin of my brothers and sisters,
deep meaning portrayed on the
legs of my cousins, the

00:27:44.370 --> 00:27:51.670
identifying marks resting on my
shoulder blade, still the
meaning escaped until coming

00:27:51.670 --> 00:27:56.830
to the Library of Congress just
four months ago. As an Eastern
Kentucky University

00:27:56.830 --> 00:28:02.300
Student in the American Sign
Language Training Program, I was
elated to be the first

00:28:02.300 --> 00:28:09.400
Interpreting Services Program
intern here at the Library of
Congress. I Micaela Viluu was

00:28:09.400 --> 00:28:16.730
the chosen student to start this
pilot off with. They took a
chance on me, and I hope that

00:28:16.730 --> 00:28:23.030
they're proud of that. And so
it truly is an honor. Thank
you, Travis, for the certificate

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:29.530
which was a surprise. Prior to
arriving I had an idea of the
task that I would be doing when
I

00:28:29.530 --> 00:28:35.230
was here. I was going to be
observing qualified
interpreters. I would team with

00:28:35.230 --> 00:28:40.900
qualified interpreters and build
relationships with professionals
in the community and

00:28:40.900 --> 00:28:48.330
language mentors. Within the
deaf community that community
actually has some

00:28:48.330 --> 00:28:55.770
parallels with the Samoan
community within the last 60
years as well. Considering that
my

00:28:55.770 --> 00:28:59.630
internship was going to be
focused on sign language, the
culture that I was looking to

00:28:59.630 --> 00:29:07.770
immerse myself in was within the
deaf community. I could have
never predicted that

00:29:07.770 --> 00:29:12.200
my time here would also lead to
an understanding of myself and
finding pieces of

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:18.200
myself that I never knew to be
missing. During the last four
months, I have researched with a

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:24.330
goal of understanding an
identity and culture that I
never truly studied nor
understood. And

00:29:24.330 --> 00:29:30.330
though all of my work, through
all of my work I am happy to say
that my journey of

00:29:30.330 --> 00:29:40.670
understanding is just beginning
and will be an ongoing and
lifetime journey. When you work

00:29:40.670 --> 00:29:46.870
here at the Library of Congress,
you might be taking for granted
the immense collections

00:29:46.870 --> 00:29:55.800
that are housed here. There are
more than a 162 million items,
more than 38 million

00:29:55.800 --> 00:30:04.570
cataloged and printed materials,
those span over 470 different
languages -- more than 70

00:30:04.570 --> 00:30:13.600
million manuscripts, and 838
miles of bookshelves. And those
are housed both here

00:30:13.600 --> 00:30:18.770
in the building. They are also
in the Jefferson. And there's
some in two locations that are
not

00:30:18.770 --> 00:30:23.870
here as well as online. So if
you find anything interesting in
the collections, you will be
able to

00:30:23.870 --> 00:30:31.600
find those as well. My research
took me through lives and laws
of Samoa, Western

00:30:31.600 --> 00:30:39.930
Samoa, and American Samoans. I
met with librarians and
curators, experts, community

00:30:39.930 --> 00:30:48.130
members. I saw myself portrayed
in the pictures of my ancestors.
I saw explanations

00:30:48.130 --> 00:30:56.200
of the iconic images portrayed
on the skins of my family
members. I saw more ancestors

00:30:56.200 --> 00:31:06.130
and architecture. Fa'asamoa,
what does it mean? The
materials that I found here at
the

00:31:06.130 --> 00:31:11.270
Library and some of you will be
able to view at the end of
today's program, have given me
an

00:31:11.270 --> 00:31:17.830
insight to Samoan culture,
community, and heritage the
Samoan way. Upon further

00:31:17.830 --> 00:31:23.000
research it seemed that many of
the materials were written about
Samoa were not actually

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:30.300
written by Samoans or even come
from Samoa itself. In fact most
of them were

00:31:30.300 --> 00:31:35.670
written by outsiders of the
Samoan community and culture.
My work in deaf studies teaches

00:31:35.670 --> 00:31:43.000
me a similar lesson in that
there can be words of difference
between materials about a

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:53.570
people in comparison with the
voice of authenticity of
material written by the people,

00:31:53.570 --> 00:32:00.500
and so it is with fa'asamoa. In
the brief time that I have let
me walk you through my

00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:05.000
research journey beginning with
manuscripts and general
collections. When first

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:10.270
researching through the Library
resources I saw many materials
from the 1800's or earlier

00:32:10.270 --> 00:32:16.770
on. Those consisted of German
and European languages. These
materials

00:32:16.770 --> 00:32:22.000
seemed to have more of a
descriptive nature than a
commentary on our culture and

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:27.970
heritage. Within the manuscript
division there is an
unprecedented collection of
Margaret

00:32:27.970 --> 00:32:33.800
Mead material. Her famous
research, "Coming to Age in
America Samoa," stands as

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:40.100
an anthropological case study on
Samoans through the eyes and
experiences of Dr. Mead

00:32:40.100 --> 00:32:48.500
and her ethnography of Samoans
in the 1920's. However, also in
the collections of her

00:32:48.500 --> 00:32:55.270
work is described by others to
be too ambitious an undertaking
even if respectfully

00:32:55.270 --> 00:33:02.600
so. Upon finding this book I
was instinctively excited.
Margaret Mead is an
anthropologist

00:33:02.600 --> 00:33:09.600
who is widely respected. So of
course in my excitement I called
my dad and realized that

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:21.100
he had a severe lack of
excitement which brought me to
some curiosity. So with the

00:33:21.100 --> 00:33:26.200
encouragement of Eric Eldritch I
was on the hunt to see why my
father would react in such

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:35.600
a way. And I found this,
"Margaret Mead's Coming to Age
in America Samoa, a

00:33:35.600 --> 00:33:41.270
Dissenting View." In his
dissension Goodman addresses the
shortcomings and

00:33:41.270 --> 00:33:47.130
assumptions made in Mead's
conclusions and final writings
after spending six months with a

00:33:47.130 --> 00:33:52.630
group of Samoan girls. Reading
this article brought me some
perspective on my father's

00:33:52.630 --> 00:33:58.730
reaction to my excitement when
finding
Mead's original work.
Nevertheless as a

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:03.800
researcher I encourage you to
read both pieces and for
yourself develop your own

00:34:03.800 --> 00:34:11.070
thoughts and opinions. And yet
even though he has a dissenting
view, some of his words

00:34:11.070 --> 00:34:20.070
still do not portray or
represent the people I love or
the culture that I have come to
value. A

00:34:20.070 --> 00:34:29.170
legal scholar defined fa'asamoa
as what you see on the screen
which would have been

00:34:29.170 --> 00:34:36.530
acceptable had it not also been
followed up with the idea of
western enlightenment. Within

00:34:36.530 --> 00:34:41.430
his writing his emphasizes the
importance of western
enlightenment on the Samoan

00:34:41.430 --> 00:34:46.870
culture. And instead of just
defining what our ways were, he
defined what our ways could

00:34:46.870 --> 00:34:53.770
be and what they may, should be.
So does this maybe present a
problem for the American

00:34:53.770 --> 00:35:00.730
Samoan or just the Samoan
culture? Who is speaking on our
behalf and how will we share

00:35:00.730 --> 00:35:06.830
fa'asamoa with the next
generation if we are not
speaking for ourselves? Through

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:12.330
everything that I have learned,
through all that I have read,
all of the materials that I have
been

00:35:12.330 --> 00:35:18.470
able to bless my hands with,
none could truly compare, could
not truly convey what

00:35:18.470 --> 00:35:27.070
fa'asamoa really means. So why
might you ask was I not able to
find one single material

00:35:27.070 --> 00:35:34.370
that would tell me where my
family is from or one part of me
that was missing? Why was I

00:35:34.370 --> 00:35:42.770
in not one material able to
change a self-label into a
personal identity? The reason
is our

00:35:42.770 --> 00:35:49.930
culture could not be found in
just one book or one map. It
isn't found in a picture dating

00:35:49.930 --> 00:35:56.900
hundreds of years back. My
culture was in everything that I
touched, that I read, and that I

00:35:56.900 --> 00:36:03.830
discussed over, everything that
I was exposed to. I have always
been a very straightforward

00:36:03.830 --> 00:36:13.100
person. My character not
appreciating ambiguity or
answers to an abstract equation.

00:36:13.100 --> 00:36:18.300
I am a person who has a question
and seeks the answer. Little
did I know that my research

00:36:18.300 --> 00:36:24.500
for what is fa'asamoa would not
give me an answer but instead
set me on a journey that I

00:36:24.500 --> 00:36:29.470
will continue to the end of my
days. This journey consisted of
challenging what I already

00:36:29.470 --> 00:36:34.600
knew about my Samoan identity,
finding dissensions to research
that many had

00:36:34.600 --> 00:36:40.070
believed to be fact,
understanding the exploration,
colonization, and in some ways

00:36:40.070 --> 00:36:46.970
the dissemination of our culture
and searching for how later I
can work to preserve and

00:36:46.970 --> 00:36:52.300
cultivate what was left. If you
look to the screens, Veteran
History Project and

00:36:52.300 --> 00:36:57.230
StoryCorps are two programs that
the Library of Congress has that
are actually useful in

00:36:57.230 --> 00:37:04.270
preserving our culture.
StoryCorps is a way that we can
tell our own stories in that my

00:37:04.270 --> 00:37:10.130
Tima can sit down and talk for
hours and hours and hours, and
that's okay, and people

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:18.870
